CustomFacts helps to build logic about environment specific configuration
-User can execyte as per the environment configuration [dev/qa/stg/prod]
Steps to create Custom facts-
-Create /etc/ansible/facts.d in Clients machine
-Create one or more custom facts inside facts.d folder
-Output of the facts file should be JSON format
-Facts file should have execution permission

Script:
(ansible-env) root@ip-172-31-17-165:~/ansible-project# cat get_version.fact 
#!/bin/bash

# Get Git Version
if command -v git >/dev/null 2>&1
then
    GIT_VERSION=$(git --version | awk '{print $3}')
else
    GIT_VERSION="not_installed"
fi

# Get Apache Version
if command -v apache2 >/dev/null 2>&1
then
    APACHE_VERSION=$(apache2 -v | head -n 1 | awk -F/ '{print $2}' | awk '{print $1}')
else
    APACHE_VERSION="not_installed"
fi

# Create JSON Output
cat << EOF
{
  "git": "$GIT_VERSION",
  "apache2": "$APACHE_VERSION"
}
EOF

Collection of Hosts is called Inventory.
Types of Inventory:
(1)Static Inventory
(2)Dynamic Inventory - Dynamic Inventory means Ansible automatically fetches the list of hosts (servers) from external sources instead of using a static file.
In real-world:
-Servers are created & deleted dynamically
-IP addresses change frequently
-Manual updates are not practical
👉 Dynamic inventory solves this problem

Dynamic inventory uses:
-Scripts (Python, Bash)
-Plugins (AWS, Azure, GCP)
👉 These return JSON format to Ansible

List all the dynamic inventory plugin list:
#ansible-doc -t inventory -l
Add Enable plugin Syntax in ansible.cfg file
#cat ansible_plugin.txt


Ansible Playbooks:
==================
Basically to execute the ansible playbook 2 ways.They are:
1)Adhoc commands
2)Playbooks
Why do you need Playbooks?
A Playbook is a YAML file where you define automation tasks step-by-step.
Instead of running commands one by one, playbooks automate everything in sequence.
Write once, use multiple times across environments (Dev, QA, Prod)
Ensures same configuration across all servers
Playbooks allow:

Conditions (when)
Loops
Variables
Roles
Running playbook multiple times gives same result (no duplication)
Infrastructure is defined in code → easy to version control (Git)

Structure of Playbook:
======================
Tasks
Play - Play is a combination of Tasks + Target
Playbooks - User wants to perform like Playbook is a combination of List or Sequesnce of plays

